The other couple joining us were a little late, so we headed to the bar to grab a drink. Both the hubby and I were a little under the weather, so we asked if we could get some tea. There was a 5-10 minute lull between each course that we were served, and we had to keep waving someone down to please check on our next course. We were seated at 9:15, and ended up leaving the restaurant well after midnight. That's three hours of attempted dining while we were completely neglected. The food was good but I'll never return. Your service sucks, Gary Danko.

I absolutely love this place. Yes, it's pricey, but I feel like it's totally worth it. So the first time I came here was a few years back, and I have to say my experience has changed from then to now (June). First off, the service here is amazing. I remember the first time coming here was when I discovered the concept of purse hangers. When we arrived and got seated, all of the ladies got purse hangers to hang our purses from the table, rather than having to keep it on the back of our seats. The servers were also rarely ever seen unless you looked like you need something, or to bring out your food. They also fold your napkin for you when you get up to go to the restroom. The first experience I had here, it felt very upscale. However, this year being my second time at this restaurant, I didn't get the same feeling. Decor changed a little, but the ambience felt more casual. As for the food. Thank goodness nothing changed there! The lobster risotto was as good as I remembered, and portion size just as big. I felt full after eating my first course! Both times I ordered a 3 course meal (with a glass of wine) and both times I felt full after my risotto. I highly recommend the risotto for the first course. For my main dish I had the Quail stuffed with Foie Gras. It was a bit heavy but it was very tasty! I've also tried their sea seared scallops and bison which are both really good as well. The scallops were cooked to perfection! For dessert , I ordered the Flambeed brandied cherries with mascarpone filled crepes which is prepared tableside. Watching it is always nice, and it tasted sooooo good the first time I had it, I had to get it again the second time around. Overall, the food here is DELICIOUS! I love it and it is worth the money you spend for the service and the (unique) food you get. Ladies always get nicely wrapped little cake to take home at the end of the night (which is also very yummy). And, if you tell them you're there for a birthday, or anniversary (went for my mom's bday and then again for my anniversary with bf) , you will get a little plate of cookies for the birthday girl or couple as well. For me, 5 stars all the way. Do know that you need to book 2 months in advance if you want a reservation!

Came here to celebrate both our Birthdays. Is hidden on the corner close to Ghiradelli Square in SF. Dim romantic lighting inside. We had 3 courses and shared a desert...which was filling. Started off with Lobster Salad with chunks of delicious lobster and a greens with burst of salt rocks in it, going well with the green sauce on the plate. She had the Risotto with Lobster and that was piping hot and each bite had a piece of delicious lobster in it...great chunks!!! Next I had the Roast Maine Lobster which was cooked to prefection full of sweet flavor and butter. The mash was nice too was felt a bit watery. She had the Coconut Thai Curry and that was full of delicious flavors too. The only bad thing about it was when eating the mushrooms....at times during chewing...you can taste some of the grit or sand, maybe either from the scallop or something else. We are not a huge fan of sand grit from the sea. We mentioned it to our server Suzanne and she apoligized for it and asked us right away if we wanted to have it redone, replaced or taken off the check. That was so sweet of her to offer, especially from a place like that. The flavors were so delicious still...we really didn't want to replace it...so she just left it off our check for us. Her Main dish was pepper duck breast, sliced so thin and pink on the inside...was not too gamie and delicious and juciey still. Was quite delicious when eaten together with the deep fried bits of the duck skin. I had the Roasted pork belly and tenderloin. It was 2 separate preparations, must eat the loin first..since is was more of a mild flavor but great soft juciey texture. Then the Pork Belly was crazy amazing!!! So crunch on the outside and melt in your mouth pork belly inside!! It was the best pork belly i've ever had. We topped it off with a chocolate souffle with table service of white chocolate vanilla sauce poured into the middle and then chocolate gnochious right after wards....so warm and light and sweet. They also surprised my wife with an extra lemon souffle cake with a candle in the middle. They also topped it off with 8 little pieces of chocolate sweet/cookie varieties. So much food...and a wrapped up banana bread to take home with us. We had Suzanne who was our main server. They also had another server who filled up out bread plate and water glasses. Another guy for the wine, another guy to replace out silverware and fold our napkins when we leave the table. Great service, great server, great food....we will definitely come back soon. Thank you GD!!!

    I absolutely love this place. Yes, it's pricey, but I feel like it's totally worth it. So the first time I came here was a few years back, and I have to say my experience has changed from then to now (June).

    First off, the service here is amazing. I remember the first time coming here was when I discovered the concept of purse hangers. When we arrived and got seated, all of the ladies got purse hangers to hang our purses from the table, rather than having to keep it on the back of our seats. The servers were also rarely ever seen unless you looked like you need something, or to bring out your food. They also fold your napkin for you when you get up to go to the restroom.

    The first experience I had here, it felt very upscale. However, this year being my second time at this restaurant, I didn't get the same feeling. Decor changed a little, but the ambience felt more casual.

    As for the food. Thank goodness nothing changed there! The lobster risotto was as good as I remembered, and portion size just as big. I felt full after eating my first course! Both times I ordered a 3 course meal (with a glass of wine) and both times I felt full after my risotto. I highly recommend the risotto for the first course. For my main dish I had the Quail stuffed with Foie Gras. It was a bit heavy but it was very tasty! I've also tried their sea seared scallops and bison which are both really good as well. The scallops were cooked to perfection! For dessert , I ordered the Flambeed brandied cherries with mascarpone filled crepes which is prepared tableside. Watching it is always nice, and it tasted sooooo good the first time I had it, I had to get it again the second time around.

    Overall, the food here is DELICIOUS! I love it and it is worth the money you spend for the service and the (unique) food you get. Ladies always get nicely wrapped little cake to take home at the end of the night (which is also very yummy). And, if you tell them you're there for a birthday, or anniversary (went for my mom's bday and then again for my anniversary with bf) , you will get a little plate of cookies for the birthday girl or couple as well. For me, 5 stars all the way. Â Do know that you need to book 2 months in advance if you want a reservation!
